One minor point on in-addr.arpa delegation:  it can only be effectively
delegated if the address ranges of the subgroups happen to fall on byte
boundaries.  If my domain happens to correspond to a class B network
that uses address mask 255.255.255.128 (subnetted along organizational
boundaries), I'd have to delegate 126 different pieces (one for each
possible address!) to the organization controlling the subdomain.  Ugly.

Of course, if you don't mind the above, then you shouldn't mind
delegating lots of disjoint pieces of your network to the
suborganization.  In the limit, you can delegate individual addresses,
and thus can have in-addr.arpa delegation even if your network is not
subnetted.  But it's messy!
